{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:53:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16712"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51964"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3233"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5940"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with gradually worsening speech difficulties over six months. He has a history of hypertension and two previous strokes. His medications include aspirin, perindopril, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His speech is strained and spastic, described as \u0027Donald Duck-like\u0027 or growling in quality. Neurological examination reveals a brisk jaw jerk reflex and other upper motor neuron signs including increased tone and hyperreflexia in all limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of dysarthria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ataxic dysarthria","Flaccid dysarthria","Hypokinetic dysarthria","Pseudobulbar dysarthria","Spastic dysarthria"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of pseudobulbar palsy, characterised by spastic, strained speech with a \u0027Donald Duck-like\u0027 quality. The presence of upper motor neuron signs, including a brisk jaw jerk, supports this diagnosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EPseudobulbar dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from bilateral lesions affecting the corticobulbar tracts, commonly seen in patients with multiple strokes or other bilateral upper motor neuron conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtaxic dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by irregular articulatory breakdown, scanning speech, and variable rate and rhythm. It is associated with cerebellar dysfunction rather than upper motor neuron signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlaccid dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E results from lower motor neuron lesions and is characterised by weak, breathy speech with nasal emission. It would not present with upper motor neuron signs like a brisk jaw jerk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokinetic dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in Parkinson\u0027s disease and is characterised by monotonous, quiet speech with reduced prosody and rushed phrases. It is not associated with spasticity or upper motor neuron signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpastic dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E is technically the same as pseudobulbar dysarthria, so this option would be redundant. In clinical practice, the term pseudobulbar dysarthria is preferred as it better describes the underlying pathophysiology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudobulbar palsy presents with spastic dysarthria characterised by strained, harsh \u0027Donald Duck\u0027 speech due to upper motor neuron lesions affecting corticobulbar pathways.","The presence of a brisk jaw jerk and other upper motor neuron signs helps distinguish pseudobulbar from bulbar palsy.","Pseudobulbar palsy typically results from bilateral cortical or subcortical lesions affecting descending motor pathways."],"references":["Ahmed A, Simmons Z. Pseudobulbar affect: prevalence and management. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2013;9:483-9. doi: 10.2147/TCRM.S53906. Epub 2013 Nov 29. PMID: 24348042; PMCID: PMC3849173.","Ishihara K, Araki S, Ihori N, Suzuki Y, Shiota J, Arai N, Nakano I, Kawamura M. Pseudobulbar dysarthria in the initial stage of motor neuron disease with dementia: a clinicopathological report of two autopsied cases. Eur Neurol. 2013;69(5):270-4. doi: 10.1159/000342220. Epub 2013 Feb 22. PMID: 23445572.","Saleem F, Munakomi S. Pseudobulbar Palsy. [Updated 2023 Aug 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553160/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51964"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51964"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T17:08:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T17:09:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"sel